Linley,<br><br>
Thank *you* for taking the step to share your feelings<br>
on your very closely emotional circumstance, and very probably the circumstance of children of other Vietnam Veterans. I mentioned your posting to my younger daughter. She asked me to bookmark the site for her, and seemed very interested. The next step will be up to her. <br><br>
Although I had begun to explore the &quot;Pandora's Box&quot; in my mind for some time, the real connection with my family, and in particular with my younger daughter, began on Father's Day in 1996. Among the usual and customary Father's Day gifts, Sara presented me with a large wrapped present that had the look and feel of a framed picture. She was very proud and excited that I open it because she had selected it herself. It was also expensive, as I was told, but that was not important.<br><br>
I removed the wrappings, and found myself staring at a picture of a middle aged man leaning against The Wall with one hand. In the reflection of The Wall were images of younger men in Vietnam uniform staring out into the world at this older man, perhaps image memories of himself, and image memories of his buddies, back there, together again, in the bond that few understand outside of the Vietnam experience.<br><br>
I looked, frozen for a while. Sara said that it was me. She was right. It was.<br><br>
I must have cried for a long time in the big family hug that came after. I felt the ice beginning to break over that self imposed emotional exile I had endured for more than 26 years.<br><br>
I have since shared my Vietnam writings with my family, and they are very much aware and support the work I am doing for myself. I find myself increasingly open. There are feelings for which I have no names yet, but they are real feelings and not the swing of rage and control I have so openly wielded in defense of the pain of fear, shame, guilt, remorse, and loss. <br><br>
There is a lot more to say than my emotions of this moment will permit, so I will have to slowly let this out over time. I will not, however, stop. I have come too far.<br><br>
Doc Del,<br><br>
Linley *did* call you a medic. I think you are the best damn medic in cyberspace. I still wear those patches you put on my mind, and some not so long ago! :) 
